# Understanding EV Charging Levels: 1, 2, and 3 Explained

One of the first things every new EV owner needs to understand is the three levels of charging. Unlike gas stations where you just "fill up," EV charging varies dramatically in speed, cost, and use case depending on which level you're using.

## Quick Summary Table

| Level | Voltage | Power Output | Typical Speed | Best For | Cost |
|-------|---------|--------------|---------------|----------|------|
| **Level 1** | 120V AC | 1.4-1.9 kW | 3-5 mi/hr | Emergency, overnight for PHEVs | Free (standard outlet) |
| **Level 2** | 240V AC | 3.3-19.2 kW | 12-60 mi/hr | Home charging, work, destinations | $500-$2,500 (install) |
| **Level 3** | DC | 50-350 kW | 100-300+ mi/30 min | Road trips, quick charging | $0.25-$0.60/kWh |

---

## Level 1 Charging (120V AC)

### What It Is

Level 1 charging uses a standard household 120V outlet—the same one you plug your phone charger or toaster into. Every EV comes with a Level 1 charging cable (often called a "trickle charger").

### The Numbers

- **Power Output:** 1.4-1.9 kW (typically 12 amps at 120V)
- **Charging Speed:** 3-5 miles of range per hour
- **Full Charge Time:** 2-4 days for most BEVs (40-80 kWh batteries)
- **Connector:** Standard NEMA 5-15 (regular three-prong outlet)

### When to Use Level 1

**Good For:**
- Emergency charging when nothing else is available
- Plug-in hybrids (PHEVs) with small batteries (10-20 kWh)
- Very short daily commutes (under 30 miles) where you charge overnight
- Maintaining charge when parked for extended periods

**Not Good For:**
- Primary charging for battery electric vehicles (BEVs)
- Recovering from low battery quickly
- Cold climates (charging is even slower in winter)

### Real-World Example

If you drive 40 miles per day and plug in for 12 hours overnight:
- **Overnight recovery:** 36-60 miles of range
- **Borderline sufficient** for this use case, but no buffer for unexpected trips

### Safety Considerations

⚠️ **Important:**
- Use a dedicated circuit (not shared with other appliances)
- Inspect outlet condition—old or damaged outlets can overheat
- Avoid extension cords (most manufacturers void warranty if used)
- Don't use outlets in garages that share circuits with garage door openers or power tools

